To understand how that works in practice, we need to follow four main steps=
: (1) turning words into numbers, (2) passing those numbers through a trans=
former network, (3) training the network at massive scale, and (4) guiding =
the finished model so it behaves safely and helpfully.
From words to numbers=E2=80=94the key is embeddings=20
Computers don=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Cknow=E2=80=9D words; they know numbers. So=
 the first job is to convert text into a form math can handle. LLMs break t=
ext into tokens=E2=80=94chunks that are usually whole words but can be sub-=
words (=E2=80=9Cun-=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cbreak=E2=80=9D, =E2=80=9Cable=E2=80=
=9D) or even punctuation. Each token gets mapped to a high-dimensional vect=
or called an embedding. Think of an embedding as a coordinate in a systems =
that captures meaning: =E2=80=9Ccat=E2=80=9D lands near =E2=80=9Ckitten,=E2=
=80=9D far from =E2=80=9Cdemocracy=E2=80=9D (well, until we run a cat for p=
resident). These coordinates aren=E2=80=99t assigned by humans; they are le=
