 close together.
Why vectors? Because they let the model use linear algebra to measure simil=
arity, combine ideas, and move through the =E2=80=9Csemantic space=E2=80=9D=
 of language. If you=E2=80=99ve heard the analogy =E2=86=92 king =E2=80=93 =
man + woman =E2=89=88 queen, that=E2=80=99s a real arithmetic operation on =
embeddings. By the time training is finished, the embedding layer has becom=
e a compressed encyclopedia of word-level knowledge, packaged in pure numbe=
rs.
The transformer engine=E2=80=94attention is all you need=20
Once the tokens are vectors, they pass into the heart of the model: a trans=
former. Introduced by Google in 2017, the transformer replaced older recurr=
ent networks by processing all tokens in parallel and letting them =E2=80=
=9Cpay attention=E2=80=9D to one another.
Each transformer layer contains two key pieces:
Self-attention: For every token, the model computes how strongly it should =
attend to every other token in the current context window. The famous =E2=
=80=9Cscaled dot-product attention=E2=80=9D takes the query vector for toke=
